    "body": "<!-- Before reporting: search existing issues and check the FAQ. -->\r\n[This](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/7286) is the closest issue I could find, but it talks about `netrw`, not the emulated terminal. Also, I wouldn't count this as a bug, it works as expected, but I think changing its behavior would make it much better, as a QoL improvement.\r\n\r\n- `nvim --version`: \r\n```bash\r\nNVIM v0.4.3\r\nBuild type: Release\r\nLuaJIT 2.1.0-beta3\r\nCompilation: /usr/bin/cc -g -O2 -fdebug-prefix-map=/build/neovim-gOb7vg/neovim-0.4.3=. -fstac\r\nk-protector-strong -Wformat -Werror=format-security -Wdate-time -D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=1 -DDISABLE\r\n_LOG -Wdate-time -D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=1 -O2 -DNDEBUG -DMIN_LOG_LEVEL=3 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -\r\nWno-unused-parameter -Wstrict-prototypes -std=gnu99 -Wshadow -Wconversion -Wmissing-prototype\r\ns -Wimplicit-fallthrough -Wvla -fstack-protector-strong -fdiagnostics-color=always -DINCLUDE_\r\nGENERATED_DECLARATIONS -D_GNU_SOURCE -DNVIM_MSGPACK_HAS_FLOAT32 -DNVIM_UNIBI_HAS_VAR_FROM -I/\r\nbuild/neovim-gOb7vg/neovim-0.4.3/build/config -I/build/neovim-gOb7vg/neovim-0.4.3/src -I/usr/\r\ninclude -I/usr/include/lua5.1 -I/build/neovim-gOb7vg/neovim-0.4.3/build/src/nvim/auto -I/buil\r\nd/neovim-gOb7vg/neovim-0.4.3/build/include\r\nCompiled by team+vim@tracker.debian.org\r\n\r\nFeatures: +acl +iconv +tui\r\nSee \":help feature-compile\"\r\n\r\n   system vimrc file: \"$VIM/sysinit.vim\"\r\n  fall-back for $VIM: \"/usr/share/nvim\"\r\n\r\nRun :checkhealth for more info\r\n```\r\n- `vim -u DEFAULTS` (version: ) behaves differently?\r\nIt doesn't. It behaves the same way.\r\nFor the record, I have nvim aliased to vim (Done by the OS itself, since I dont have their `vim` package installed), so that may be why it behaves the same way. I just don't know how to reverse this without uninstalling `nvim`.\r\n- Operating system/version:\r\nPop!_OS 20.10\r\n- Terminal name/version: `gnome-terminal`, 3.36.2 \r\n- `$TERM`: `xterm-256color`\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce using `nvim -u NORC`\r\n```viml\r\nnvim -u NORC\r\n:set mouse=a\r\n:sp term://bash\r\n \" click out of terminal split \"\r\ni\r\n \" click  in terminal split \"\r\n```\r\nBasically, with `:set mouse=a`, create a terminal split and switch into it by clicking it with the mouse while in insert mode in another split\r\n\r\n### Actual behaviour\r\nSince the terminal buffer cannot be modified from insert mode, if you type anything, nvim gives an error about trying to modify a buffer with modifiable off\r\n```\r\nE21: Cannot make changes, 'modifiable' is off\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\nSince Insert mode in a terminal buffer is useless, make it so when you switch splits this way, you enter into the terminal mode where you can type commands to the shell. Supposedly, if you were in insert mode and switched to the terminal split, it's because you want to keep typing something, so having to dismiss the error messages, press `Esc` and then `i` again can be annoying.\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43295942/108605611-81ddbe80-73b5-11eb-828a-0dc2021d3af0.png)\r\n*Undesirable outcome*\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43295942/108605614-902bda80-73b5-11eb-8cbe-59be80f9f917.png)\r\n*Inside terminal in Insert mode*\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43295942/108605768-9b333a80-73b6-11eb-971b-6352bfcc7a17.png)\r\n*The Terminal mode, what I suggest is the desirable outcome*",
